04096nam a22005535i 9780231540742DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015020789  a(OCoLC)1013955135  a97802315407427 a10.7312/daya167122doi  a(DE-B1597)458300  a(OCoLC)940679960  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aSF422.86b.D93 2016 4aSF422.86b.D39 2015 7aPHI0050002bisacsh1 aDayan, Colin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWith Dogs at the Edge of Life /cColin Dayan. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b38 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tby way of beginning -- tPart One. Like a Dog -- tChapter One. Dogs and Light -- tChapter Two. Back Talking Like I Did -- tChapter Three. They Killed My Dog -- tPart Two. When Law Comes to Visit -- tChapter Four. Dead Dogs -- tChapter Five. Speaking About Extinction -- tChapter Six. Fable for the End of a Breed -- tPart Three. Pariah Dogs -- tChapter Seven. Through the Eyes of Dogs -- tChapter Eight. If I Sense the Beauty -- tCoda -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this original and provocative book, Colin Dayan tackles head-on the inexhaustible world, at once tender and fierce, of dogs and humans. We follow the tracks of dogs in the bayous of Louisiana, the streets of Istanbul, and the humane societies of the United States, and in the memories and myths of the humans who love them. Dayan reorients our ethical and political assumptions through a trans-species engagement that risks as much as it promises. She makes a powerful case for questioning what we think of as our deepest-held beliefs and, with dogs in the lead, unsettles the dubious promises of liberal humanism.Moving seamlessly between memoir, case law, and film, Dayan takes politics and animal studies in a new direction—one that gives us glimpses of how we can think beyond ourselves and with other beings. Her unconventional perspective raises hard questions and renews what it means for any animal or human to live in the twenty-first century. Nothing less than a challenge for us to confront violence and suffering even in the privileged precincts of modernity, this searing and lyrical book calls for another way to think the world. Theoretically sophisticated yet aimed at a broad readership, With Dogs at the Edge of Life illuminates how dogs—and their struggles—take us beyond sentimentality and into a form of thought that can make a difference to our lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnimal welfarezUnited States. 0aDog ownersxPsychology. 0aDogsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aHuman-animal relationshipsxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/daya1671240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231540742423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231540742.jpg  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles